    <segment id="1" parent="31" relname="span">
The intuitiveness of a design increases the efficiency and ease of use
of a product by preventing the user from having to manually complete a
certain process, taking unecessary additional steps in completing a
process, or repeating a process.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="27" relname="background"> For example, a user wishes to play a
song using an mp3 player on their computer.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="20" relname="circumstance"> When the Open option on the
music player&apos;s interface is clicked,</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="33" relname="span"> a choice is given of which folder
to open the file from.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="25" relname="span">  The user proceeds to open Folder A</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> where there
are countless of stored files including word processing documents, HTML
files,  pictures, videos, and music.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="27" relname="span"> An intuitive music player would
&quot;know&quot; that the user is only looking for music files and display only
such files in the Open dialog box.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="22" relname="circumstance"> The program would know that when a
user wants to open a file, </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="18" relname="span">it can only look for mp3 files in the chosen
folder,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="19" relname="span"> not .txt, .ppt, mpeg, .wav, etc.,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="concession"> even if all those files
coexisted in the same folder as the mp3 files.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="27" relname="elaboration"> This intuitiveness is
also a form of error prevention that keeps the user from sorting out
through incompatible file types, or risking damage to files by opening
them with wrong application.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="28" relname="span"> 

Another example is when a particular application is given a command to
open an incompatible file type.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> Or when there is not enough resources
available to perform a process.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="antithesis"> In intuitive program will know its
limitations and will not attempt to open the file regardless of the
chances of freezing or shutting down the system.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="29" relname="span"> Instead, the intuitive
application would warn the user of its limitations with an error
message, further directions, or even call on the operating system to
display a list of available options,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="14" relname="elaboration"> such as a display of other programs
that may (or may not) be able open that particular file type.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="30" relname="span">  

Still another example of intuitiveness relates to memorability</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="15" relname="elaboration"> when an
application remembers your login, password, or demographic information
to prevent redundancy; </segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="15" relname="elaboration">also, when the AOL client application alerts the
user that they&apos;ve got mail before having a chance to go to the mailbox.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="15" relname="nonvolitional-result">
Such transparent processes provide subtle instances of  intuitiveness.</segment>
